bib_record.title: Study of Reaction Mechanisms Involved in the Ca40(d,p)Ca41 Reaction

free_txt: Protons from reactions in the target passed
through thin aluminum foil and were detected in
CsI(Tl) scintillation counters.
Angular distributions were taken at 7.5 degree
intervals using two counters which were carefully
checked to have equal efficiencies. Excitation curves
above 2.25 MeV were taken with four counters set at 0,
45, 90, and 135 degrees to the incident beam. Below
2.25 MeV, counters were set at 30, 90, and 150
degrees. The biases on the single-channel
pulse-height analyzers used were checked periodically
by comparison with a 256-channel pulse-height
analyzer to be sure that only protons from the ground
state of Ca41 were detected.
A carefully weighed CaF2 target was used. The targets
were mounted at 45 degrees to the incident beam in
the center of a scattering chamber of 6-in. diameter
which had ports of 0.25-in. diameter every 7.5
degrees. Ca-40 has 97% abundance, so using Ca-40 (as
the authors did) can be justified, assuming that the
minor isotopes would not make much difference.
Statistical errors are of the order of magnitude
indicated by the size of the points, or less.
The Ca target used was 25 keV thick to 3-MeV
deuterons and was evaporated on a thin Au backing.
